<HEADLINE>
MORE MALE JACKPOT WINNERS THAN FEMALES: TAIWAN LOTTERY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 23 (CNA) 05/23/07  19:33:05 (By Flor Wang)
</P>
<P>
There have been more male winners of big Taiwan lottery prizes
than females during the first four months of this year, with 72
percent of the 163 winners being men, Taiwan Lottery Co. Ltd.
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Taiwan Lottery Co., which was entrusted to run the
country's Public Welfare Lottery services from Jan. 1, 2007, most
of the male winners live in Taipei City and Taipei County,
accounting for 27 percent and 17 percent of the total,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some 29 percent of the male winners who got large prizes (over
NT$5 million) in the January-April period are aged between 40-49
and work in the service sector or as freelancers, company
statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 percent of Taiwan's big prizewinners purchase lottery
tickets every week, spending from NT$100-NT$500. Many of them are
under the star sign Sagittarius and of blood type B, according to
company officials.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the disposal of the lottery cash prizes, 24 percent of
the winners deposit the cash in bank accounts, followed by those
who use the money to repay house loans, invest, purchase real-
estate or donate to charity, according to company statistics.
</P>
